Posted: Sun Mar 31, 2013 8:42 am
Brewing a very non-traditional Barleywine this morning. A friend has a rum barrel from a local distillery he wanted to age in, so figured I'd throw something together this weekend. The recipe is a real hodge-podge of stuff I had available and what I could scavenge locally (Iowa has a dearth of local homebrew shops). That said, what I could procure should get me somewhere close to what I was envisioning for flavor. Looking for a raisiny/chocolate/toffee flavor profile, inspired in part by Sucaba and Old Numbskull, with a bit of a belgian twist.Here's the crack-addled recipe (spoilered for those with delicate sensibilities )
Spoiler: show
Code:Old Hodgepodge - 10 gallon Iowegian Barleywine------------------30 lbs Golden Promise3.3 lbs Golden Pilsen LME3 lbs Golden Pilsen DME3 lbs Extra Light DME3 lbs Special B2 lbs Cara802 lbs Corn Sugar1 lb Chocolate Malt1 lb Maple Syrup2 oz Nugget at 60 minutes of boil8 oz "Raw" (Unprocessed) Cacao powder at flameout8 oz Cacao nibs in SecondaryWhite Labs British Ale and Wyeast English Ale yeasts mixed together in a starterStep mash 45 minutes at 146 then 1 hour at 157. Boil for 2 hoursBeersmith is estimating a OG of 1.143 and 16.3% ABV at 70% efficiency
Finished brewing it, between the cold water, step mash, super slow sparge and doing everything outside on a windy day it took about 10 hours. Refractometer doesn't go high enough! I'm over 30 Brix, which is 1.130, definitely thinking I hit my target though. Now to wait on the yeast and father time.
Nutrimentia
