I think (hope?) I screwed up my Heavy Seas Loose Cannon inspired IPA 2 weeks ago when I let the temperature of the mash get away from me. It jumped up to 180 about 20 minutes into the mash and I couldn't get it down for a long time. I don't have a hydrometer currently so I can't measure gravities, but my Safale 04 yeast didn't do anything, even after repitching. THe yeast is getting 2 years old but the previous batch with the same aged Safale05 burbled like gangbusters. I'm just hoping that I shut down the mash and thus there's no fermentables rather than bad yeast.This last weekend I tried my Arrogant Bastard inspired recipe but got distracted while I was on the phone and weighed out too much grain. I usually go with a 7 gallon mash (that's what's needed to cover the mash tun's built in thermo prior to adding the grain) but thought I'd try a 5 gallon mash this time. the combination of a too much grain (maybe 1 kilogram extra? I'm not sure but it felt like A LOT) resulted in a hugely thick mash. I over-reacted and added a few more gallons of water but then the flow through pump kept stalling out, even if I kept stirring to avoid clogging the false bottom. If I'd had time I'd have dumped it and restarted but there wasn't enough time to reset the equipment and make it to the homebrew tasting we had planned for that evening. So now I'm all paranoid about my beer making. I've only got about 6 or 7 weekends of brewing left before I have to pack up my kit to prepare to move to the next post. Most of that I won't even get to drink and will have to leave to friends as I move on. Since Iv'e got a year of language training before getting to the next post, I won't see my gear for a loooong time. kmeeks
