Posted: Tue Apr 02, 2013 6:48 pm
Jumping above 170 for even a few minutes halts the enzyme activity necessary to convert the starch in the barley into soluble sugar. Rising quickly during the initial mash cycle is the worst time for that to happen, as you don't allow any time for the sugar to be produced. John Palmer covers the saccharification stage really well here http://www.howtobrew.com/section3/chapter14-5.html At 180 your grain was essentially toast and all you were extracting were tannins from the husk. There might be some sugar in it, but it's not going to taste good. I would dump that batch and not be concerned about the yeast. Dry yeast can last A LONG TIME. I wouldn't even blink at using a 2 year old package. The mash temps though, were I you, I'd have started adding ice the moment I broke 160. If I hadn't noticed and was 20 minutes in and at 180 I'd have dumped it and called it a day.The below table is from the start of Chapter 14 on mashing, but shows the temperature ranges for the various enzymes in barley, and what they accomplish.
Spoiler: show
Code:Enzyme OptimumTemperatureRange Working pH Range FunctionPhytase 86-126°F 5.0-5.5 Lowers the mash pH. No longer used.Debranching (var.) 95-113°F 5.0-5.8 Solubilization of starches.Beta Glucanase 95-113°F 4.5-5.5 Best gum breaking rest.Peptidase 113-131°F 4.6-5.3 Produces Free Amino Nitrogen (FAN).Protease 113-131°F 4.6-5.3 Breaks up large proteins that form haze.Beta Amylase 131-150°F 5.0-5.5 Produces maltose.Alpha Amylase 154-162°F 5.3-5.7 Produces a variety of sugars, including maltose.
The second batch with the stuck mash, you're probably fine though maybe on the low end of efficiency. You really want to keep above 1.25 qts water/lb grain, for sugar extraction and for flow on mash out. My above massive barley wine was right on 1.33 (a pretty common suggested happy medium). You don't mention your grain bill, but 20 quarts of water would be a max of about 16lbs of grain. Most of the suggested recipes I'm reading for Arrogant clones are in the 14-15lb range, so if you overshot the high end by 2.2 lbs you'd definitely have a thicker than suggested mash but nothing insanely over the top. Adding more water probably didn't hurt anything, so long as the temperature of the added water was on the money with your mash temps.Everyone makes mistakes, I wouldn't stress them. The Loose Cannon is probably a lost cause, but the Arrogant should be fine (though probably not going to be spot on for what you were going for).
Nutrimentia
